<b><i>Table 5</i> – NV Index handles for FDO Credentials</b>

Note that different handle values are used for different key sizes,
the TPM SHALL be provisioned with only one key size for each FDO
parameter. The Device key and its corresponding Device certificate are
stored at the same offset within their respective handle range. 

<div class="informative">

The DCOV NV index (`0x01D10002`) and FDO Certificate NV index
(`0x01D10005`) are OPTIONAL and have limited practical utility:

* The Ownership Voucher is normally held by the owner server, not the
  device. The FDO protocol does not require the device to have a local
  copy. See [[#OV_LABEL]] for the narrow supply-chain use case.
* Ownership Vouchers routinely exceed 1 KB, which exceeds the NV
  storage budget of many TPMs (especially resource-constrained
  models).
* The device certificate chain is already embedded in the Ownership
  Voucher. Storing a separate copy in TPM NV is redundant for FDO
  protocol operation.
* Neither index contains secret material. Their integrity is
  guaranteed by cryptographic signatures, not by TPM access controls.
* The device can re-obtain the Ownership Voucher at any time by
  re-running TO2. For local caching, the OV MAY be stored on
  non-TPM media (filesystem, flash partition) without compromising
  the TPM's security guarantees for actual secrets.

If this index is used, it SHOULD contain the device's X.509
certificate (e.g., IDevID or LDevID certificate) rather than the
Ownership Voucher. Implementations SHOULD be aware of TPM NV size
constraints when provisioning this index.

</div>



## Authorization for FDO Credentials ## {#Authorization_LABEL}

### Key Authorization ### {#KEYAUTH_LABEL}

FDO keys (Device Key and HMAC key) are persistent TPM objects with
`userWithAuth=1` and empty authValue (see [[#KEYTEMPL_LABEL]]).
Key usage requires only a password or HMAC session with the
(empty) authValue. No policy session is required for signing or
HMAC operations.

<table class="data longlastcol" id="TABKEYAUTH">
  <tr>
   <td><strong>Operation</strong>
   </td>
   <td><strong>FDO Device key</strong>
   </td>
   <td><strong>FDO HMAC key</strong>
   </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>Store
   </td>
   <td>Persistent object at <code>DCTPM.DeviceKeyHandle</code>
   </td>
   <td>Persistent object at <code>DCTPM.HMACKeyHandle</code>
   </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>Persist (REQUIRED)
   </td>
   <td>TPM2_EvictControl w/ Owner authorization
   </td>
   <td>TPM2_EvictControl w/ Owner authorization
   </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>Use
   </td>
   <td>TPM2_Sign w/ empty authValue
   </td>
   <td>TPM2_HMAC w/ empty authValue
   </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>Delete
   </td>
   <td>TPM2_EvictControl w/ Owner authorization, or TPM2_Clear
   </td>
   <td>TPM2_EvictControl w/ Owner authorization, or TPM2_Clear
   </td>
  </tr>
</table>

<b><i>Table 6</i> – Authorization for FDO keys</b>

<div class="informative">

Administrative operations on FDO keys (e.g., changing authValue via
`TPM2_ObjectChangeAuth`) require a policy session because
`adminWithPolicy=1`. This prevents rogue software from silently
locking the key by setting an unknown password, while leaving normal
key usage unrestricted.

Provisioning entities MAY set a non-empty authValue on keys if
deployment-specific access control is required. In that case, all FDO
client software must be configured with the authValue.

Key creation methods are implementation-specific; see [[#DEVKEY_LABEL]]
for the Device key and [[#HMAC_LABEL]] for the HMAC key. Key templates
are defined in [[#KEYTEMPL_LABEL]].

</div>

### NV Index Authorization ### {#NVAUTH_LABEL}

The DCTPM NV index stores all FDO credential data in a single
CBOR-encoded structure (see [[#FDOCRED]]). Its NV attributes
(see [[#Attributes_LABEL]]) provide the following access model:

<table class="data longlastcol" id="TABDATAUTH">
  <tr>
   <td><strong>Operation</strong>
   </td>
   <td><strong>DCTPM NV Index</strong>
   </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>Create
   </td>
   <td>TPM2_NV_DefineSpace w/ Platform or Owner authorization
   </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>Read
   </td>
   <td>TPM2_NV_Read w/ Owner authorization or NV index authValue
   </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>Write
   </td>
   <td>TPM2_NV_Write w/ Owner authorization or NV index authValue
   </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>Delete
   </td>
   <td>TPM2_NV_UndefineSpace w/ Platform or Owner authorization
   </td>
  </tr>
</table>

<b><i>Table 7</i> – Authorization for DCTPM NV index</b>

The default NV authValue is empty, allowing any software with TPM access
to read and write the DCTPM index. This is appropriate during Device
Initialization and onboarding, when the FDO client needs unrestricted
access.

<div class="informative">

**Access restriction with WriteLock:** In deployments where a
boot-time OS agent (such as a systemd service or init script) is
responsible for FDO onboarding and credential management, the agent
MAY use `TPM2_NV_WriteLock` after completing its operations to prevent
other applications from modifying FDO credentials for the remainder
of the boot cycle. The write lock is cleared automatically on the
next TPM reset (boot). This allows the agent to perform key rotation
during onboarding while preventing unprivileged applications from
altering or corrupting credentials.

**Optional NV indices:** If the DCOV or FDO Device Certificate NV
indices are provisioned (see [[#OV_LABEL]] and [[#DEVCERT_LABEL]]),
they use Owner authorization for read and write. These indices are
rarely used in practice and are not required for FDO protocol
operation.

</div>



## FDO Active flag ## {#FDOACTIVE}

The FDO Active flag is the `DCActive` field within the DCTPM CBOR
structure (see [[#FDOCRED]]). It is a boolean value: `true` indicates
that FDO onboarding should be attempted at next boot, `false`
indicates FDO is inactive. The FDO client reads and writes this field by
updating the DCTPM NV index.



## FDO Public Device Credentials ## {#FDOCRED}

The FDO Public Device Credentials (defined in [[#CREDOVIEW_LABEL]])
are stored as an NV Index in the TPM. The NV Index data field SHALL
contain the DCTPM structure as is specified in CBOR DCCL below.   The
CDDL types protver, Guid, RendezvousInfo, and Hash are as defined in
the FDO 1.1 specification [[!FDO-Specification]]. 


```
    ; Magic value 0x46444F31 ("FDO1") identifies this as an FDO DCTPM
    ; structure version 1. Readers MUST verify this value before
    ; interpreting the remaining fields. This disambiguates FDO data
    ; from other uses of the same NV index and provides versioning
    ; for future structure changes.
    DCTPM = [
        DCTPMMagic:      uint,    ; SHALL be 0x46444F31 ("FDO1")
        DCActive:        bool,
        DCProtVer:       protver,
        DCDeviceInfo:    tstr,
        DCGuid:          Guid
        DCRVInfo:        RendezvousInfo,
        DCPubKeyHash:    Hash
        DeviceKeyType:   uint
        DeviceKeyHandle: uint
        HMACKeyHandle:   uint
    ]

```

**NV Index sizing and hierarchy considerations:**

The DCTPM NV index MAY be created under Platform hierarchy (with
`TPMA_NV_PLATFORMCREATE=1`) or Owner hierarchy (without). The choice
affects durability and flexibility:

* **Platform-created** (`PLATFORMCREATE=1`): Survives `TPM2_Clear`.
  Owner can read/write if `OWNERWRITE=1` and `OWNERREAD=1` are set,
  but CANNOT delete or resize the index. The creating entity MUST
  allocate sufficient space for future credential updates (minimum
  384 bytes, 512 bytes RECOMMENDED).

* **Owner-created** (no `PLATFORMCREATE`): Owner can delete and
  recreate with a different size as needed. Does NOT survive
  `TPM2_Clear`.

Implementations reading the DCTPM NV index SHALL first verify that
the `DCTPMMagic` field equals `0x46444F31`. If the magic value does
not match, the index does not contain valid FDO credentials and SHALL
be treated as if no FDO credentials are present.

## FDO Device Key ## {#DEVKEY_LABEL}

<div class="informative">

FDO uses a **Device Attestation Key (DAK)** to identify the device
during onboarding protocols. Alternatively, an IDevID or LDevID key
may be used as the Device key; the creation and management of such
keys is outside the scope of this document.

This section defines the DAK: a purpose-built ECC signing key stored
in the TPM and used exclusively for FDO protocol operations.

<span style="text-decoration:underline;">DeviceKeyType field:</span>

The `DCTPM.DeviceKeyType` field is informational metadata indicating
what kind of key is referenced by `DCTPM.DeviceKeyHandle`. It does
not affect protocol behavior -- the FDO client uses the key at the handle
regardless of type. The field is useful for credential management
decisions (e.g., whether the key can be rotated):

* **Type 0 (DAK)**: A purpose-built FDO key. Can be rotated or
  replaced by the Owner post-onboarding.
* **Type 1 (IDevID)**: A permanent hardware identity provisioned by
  the TPM or platform manufacturer. Not rotatable.
* **Type 2 (LDevID)**: An owner-provisioned device identity per the
  TCG DevID specification. Rotatability depends on the Owner's
  policy and TCG DevID key management practices.

<span style="text-decoration:underline;">Lifetime:</span>

The Device key's lifetime depends on the deployment model:

Case 1: The Device key is intended for long-lived lifecycle
management, including re-onboarding, credential reuse, and survival
across factory resets. The key persists through multiple ownership
transfers and onboarding cycles. If durability across `TPM2_Clear`
is required, the key and DCTPM NV index should be created under the
Platform hierarchy (see durability considerations below). An IDevID
may be appropriate for this case.

Case 2: The Device key is intended to be replaced when device
ownership changes or when privacy requires unlinkability across
owners. A new DAK or LDevID is provisioned by each Owner, and the
previous key is discarded. This supports privacy-preserving resale
scenarios.

<span style="text-decoration:underline;">TPM key creation:</span>

The DAK is created and persisted in the TPM by the provisioning
entity. The entity selects the TPM hierarchy appropriate to their
role:

* **TPM vendor**: The Endorsement hierarchy is natural, since the
  vendor owns the EPS and can ensure key stability.
* **OEM / Device manufacturer**: The Platform hierarchy is natural,
  since the OEM controls Platform authorization during manufacturing.
* **Supply chain entity or end user**: The Owner hierarchy is
  natural, since these entities typically operate under Owner
  authorization.

**TPM2_Clear durability considerations:**

The choice of hierarchy and NV index attributes determines whether
FDO credentials survive a `TPM2_Clear` operation:

* **Persistent objects** evicted under **Platform** authorization
  survive `TPM2_Clear`. Persistent objects evicted under **Owner**
  authorization are **removed** by `TPM2_Clear`.
* **NV indices** with `TPMA_NV_PLATFORMCREATE` set survive
  `TPM2_Clear`. NV indices without this attribute are **removed**.
* The **Endorsement Primary Seed (EPS)** is not changed by
  `TPM2_Clear`. The **Storage Primary Seed (SPS)** is reset,
  meaning Owner hierarchy primary keys would derive differently
  even if recreated with the same template.
* The **Platform Primary Seed (PPS)** is not changed by
  `TPM2_Clear` (only by `TPM2_ChangePPS`).

Ideally, FDO credentials and keys should be created under the
Platform hierarchy with `TPMA_NV_PLATFORMCREATE`, so that they
survive `TPM2_Clear`. However, not all provisioning entities have
Platform authorization -- resellers, supply chain integrators, and
end users typically only have Owner authorization. In such cases,
credentials created under Owner hierarchy will function correctly
but will be destroyed if `TPM2_Clear` is executed (e.g., during
factory acceptance testing, OS reinstallation, or downstream
reprovisioning). Provisioning entities choosing Owner hierarchy
should document this constraint and ensure that any downstream
process that may invoke `TPM2_Clear` is aware that FDO credentials
will need to be re-provisioned afterward.

**Roles and Responsibilities:**

<table class="data longlastcol">
  <tr>
   <td><strong>Role</strong></td>
   <td><strong>Provisions</strong></td>
   <td><strong>Typical Hierarchy</strong></td>
   <td><strong>Survives TPM2_Clear?</strong></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>TPM Vendor</td>
   <td>IDevID, EK</td>
   <td>Endorsement</td>
   <td>Yes (EPS-derived)</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>Platform OEM</td>
   <td>DAK (optional), DCTPM NV index</td>
   <td>Platform</td>
   <td>Yes (PLATFORMCREATE=1)</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>Supply Chain</td>
   <td>DAK or credential updates</td>
   <td>Platform or Owner</td>
   <td>Depends on hierarchy</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>Device Owner</td>
   <td>LDevID, credential reuse, Active flag</td>
   <td>Owner</td>
   <td>No (reset on TPM2_Clear)</td>
  </tr>
</table>

Each role operates within its natural hierarchy. The spec does not
require any role to borrow another role's hierarchy.

</div>

<span style="text-decoration:underline;">Requirements:</span>

The result of Device key provisioning SHALL be a persistent ECC signing
key object in the TPM, with the object attributes
defined in [[#KEYTEMPL_LABEL]] (including `fixedTPM=1`,
`sensitiveDataOrigin=1`, `userWithAuth=1`, `adminWithPolicy=1`).
The persistent handle SHALL be recorded in `DCTPM.DeviceKeyHandle`.

The Device key SHALL be persisted within the TPM via
`TPM2_EvictControl`.

When an LDevID or IDevID key is **not** used as the Device key:

1. The Device key SHALL be an ECC signing key with the object attributes and template specified in [[#KEYTEMPL_LABEL]], including `fixedTPM=1`, `sensitiveDataOrigin=1`, `userWithAuth=1`, and `adminWithPolicy=1`.
2. The Device key SHALL be persisted within the TPM via `TPM2_EvictControl`. The persistent handle SHALL be recorded in `DCTPM.DeviceKeyHandle`.
3. `DCTPM.DeviceKeyType` SHALL be set to 0 (DAK).

<div class="informative">

<span style="text-decoration:underline;">Storage:</span>

The Device key is persisted in the TPM during provisioning
(for the persistent object handle, refer to [[#Handles_LABEL]]).
The persistent handle is recorded in `DCTPM.DeviceKeyHandle` so that
any compliant client can locate and use the key without knowledge of
how the provisioning entity created it (hierarchy, template, Primary
vs. ordinary).

</div>

<div class="informative">

**Creation Methods:**

There are two valid approaches for creating the Device key. Both
produce an identical outcome: a persistent ECC signing key at the
specified handle, usable with empty authValue.

*Approach 1: Child key under a deterministic parent (RECOMMENDED).*
The provisioning entity creates a standard storage primary (SRK) via
`TPM2_CreatePrimary`, then creates a child signing key via
`TPM2_Create`, loads it (`TPM2_Load`), and persists it
(`TPM2_EvictControl`). The child key is generated from the TPM's
RNG, so each key is unique and unpredictable. The parent (SRK) is
not needed at runtime — it is only required during creation and
loading. This approach is compatible with all major TPM stacks,
including Windows, WinPE, and common middleware.

*Approach 2: Primary key with a unique string.*
The provisioning entity creates the Device key directly as a Primary
key via `TPM2_CreatePrimary` with a random value in the `unique`
field of the template. The unique string randomizes the derived key
material, providing a different key for each device and enabling
key rotation (by changing the unique string and recreating the
Primary). This approach is RECOMMENDED as a countermeasure against
key rollback: if the persistent object is ever evicted, the same
key can be recreated from the same seed + template + unique string.
However, some TPM stacks (notably WinPE) reject or mishandle
`TPM2_CreatePrimary` calls with non-standard unique values.

**Note:** If a provisioning entity creates a Primary key *without* a
unique string (i.e., with a zero or empty unique field), the resulting
key is deterministic and identical across all devices sharing the same
Primary Seed and template. This is inherently undetectable by the
FDO client and unavoidable if the implementation cannot supply a
unique string, but it means the key cannot be rotated and is
susceptible to rollback. Implementations that cannot use unique
strings SHOULD use the child key approach instead.

**Rotation:**
- *Child key:* Create a new child under the SRK, evict the old
  persistent key, persist the new one at the same handle.
- *Primary with unique string:* Generate a new random unique string,
  call `TPM2_CreatePrimary` with the new value, evict the old
  persistent key, persist the new one at the same handle.

In both cases the DCTPM NV index and Ownership Voucher are updated
accordingly.

</div>

**Client interoperability:** FDO client software (the FDO client) SHALL locate
the Device key by reading `DCTPM.DeviceKeyHandle` and calling
`TPM2_ReadPublic` at that handle. The client does not need to know
the key's creation method, parent key, or hierarchy. Once persisted,
the key is used solely by handle with empty-auth HMAC session
authorization (see [[#KEYTEMPL_LABEL]]).


**Note:** Default Templates for the FDO Device key are defined for ECC NIST P-256 and NIST P-384 



## FDO Device Key Preference Order ## {#KEYPREF_LABEL}

<div class="informative">

FDO supports multiple device key types: a purpose-built FDO Device
Attestation Key (DAK), an LDevID (locally significant device identity),
or an IDevID (permanent hardware identity). When multiple key types
are present in the TPM, the FDO software needs a defined priority
to determine which key to use.

The preference order follows a natural specificity gradient:

* **DAK** is the most specific: it exists solely for FDO and is
  provisioned by whichever entity (TPM vendor, OEM, supply chain,
  end user) decided to enable FDO on this device.

* **LDevID** is owner-scoped: it was created by the current device
  operator and represents their relationship with the device. It
  follows TCG standards for locally significant identity.

* **IDevID** is the fallback: it is the permanent hardware identity,
  always present (unless deliberately wiped), and proves the device's
  manufacturing provenance. It serves as a bootstrap identity for
  initial onboarding, not as the long-term operational FDO credential.

</div>

FDO client software discovering device keys in the TPM SHALL use the
following order of preference:

<table class="data longlastcol" id="TABKEYPREF">
  <tr>
   <td><strong>Priority</strong>
   </td>
   <td><strong>Key Type</strong>
   </td>
   <td><strong>DeviceKeyType</strong>
   </td>
   <td><strong>Description</strong>
   </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>1
   </td>
   <td>DAK (Device Attestation Key)
   </td>
   <td>0
   </td>
   <td>Purpose-built key for FDO, provisioned at any point in the device lifecycle.
   The FDO client locates the DAK via the persistent handle recorded in
   `DCTPM.DeviceKeyHandle`.
   </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>2
   </td>
   <td>LDevID
   </td>
   <td>2
   </td>
   <td>Locally significant device identity, provisioned by the current Owner.
   Management of LDevID keys follows the TCG DevID specification and is outside
   the scope of this document.
   </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>3
   </td>
   <td>IDevID
   </td>
   <td>1
   </td>
   <td>Permanent hardware identity, provisioned by the TPM or platform manufacturer.
   Used as a bootstrap identity when no DAK or LDevID is available.
   </td>
  </tr>
</table>

<b><i>Table 1a</i> -- Device Key Preference Order</b>

The FDO client SHALL check for each key at its standard handle. It SHALL use
the first key it finds, in priority order. The `DCTPM.DeviceKeyType`
field indicates which key type is currently active.

<div class="informative">

The preference order accommodates manufacturers and operators at
different levels of TCG adoption, and supports distinct post-onboarding
identity strategies with different tradeoffs.

**Starting Points -- What the Manufacturer Provides:**

Some manufacturers may not have existing TCG device identity
infrastructure. These manufacturers simply provision a DAK during
manufacturing and are done -- FDO uses the DAK directly.

Other manufacturers may already embrace the TCG-standard IDevID. In
this case, the manufacturer SHOULD NOT be required to create a
separate DAK when they already have a perfectly good device identity.
FDO can use the IDevID directly as the device key for initial
onboarding. The IDevID serves as a bootstrap identity: it gets the
device through its first TO2, after which the Owner takes control.

A manufacturer MAY provision both an IDevID and a DAK. This is
appropriate when the manufacturer wants to provide a permanent
hardware identity (IDevID) AND an explicitly rotatable FDO identity
(DAK). The IDevID, created under the Endorsement hierarchy, is
permanently bound to the Endorsement Primary Seed (EPS) and cannot
be rotated or scrubbed -- it is the device's immutable birth
certificate. A DAK, by contrast, is physically rotatable (by creating
a new child key and evicting the old one) and can be fully scrubbed
from the device. An LDevID
can only *mask* the IDevID (by taking priority), but cannot erase
it. A DAK therefore serves a different purpose: it provides a
device identity that is explicitly designed to be replaceable.

Note that the DAK is created at the discretion of the platform
manufacturer (not the TPM manufacturer), and the manufacturer
controls the persistent handle and hierarchy under which the DAK
is created. Manufacturers SHOULD NOT protect the DAK against
rotation (i.e., the DAK's persistent handle SHOULD be evictable
by the Owner hierarchy), but this is ultimately the manufacturer's
policy decision. Implementations attempting DAK rotation SHOULD
handle the case where rotation fails because the manufacturer
created the key under a hierarchy the Owner cannot access.

**Post-Onboarding -- Two Paths for Identity Management:**

After the first successful TO2, the Owner has two distinct strategies
for managing device identity going forward:

*Path 1: Add an LDevID (additive, reversible).*
The Owner creates an LDevID in the TPM following TCG DevID practices.
FDO uses the LDevID (priority 2) instead of the IDevID (priority 3).
Critically, the IDevID is not touched -- it remains in the TPM
exactly as the manufacturer left it. This means the Owner can wipe
the LDevID at any time and the device returns to its factory-delivered
state (IDevID). This is a true **factory reset** capability.

*Path 2: Rotate the DAK (destructive, one-way).*
The Owner creates a new child key under the deterministic parent
primary, evicts the old DAK from its persistent handle, and persists
the new key at the same handle. The old DAK -- and with it, the
original manufacturing identity -- is gone. This is inherently
**one-way**:
there is no returning to the factory-provisioned identity because it
has been overwritten. This is sometimes desirable for supply chain
anonymity (the device's origin is scrubbed), but it means the device
can never be restored to its as-delivered state.

**The Key Asymmetry:**

<table class="data longlastcol">
  <tr>
   <td></td>
   <td><strong>LDevID (additive)</strong></td>
   <td><strong>DAK rotation (destructive)</strong></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>IDevID preserved?</td>
   <td>Yes -- untouched</td>
   <td>N/A (device may not have IDevID)</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>Factory reset possible?</td>
   <td>Yes -- wipe LDevID, fall back to IDevID</td>
   <td>No -- original DAK is gone</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>Supply chain anonymity?</td>
   <td>Partial -- IDevID still exists in TPM</td>
   <td>Full -- old identity scrubbed</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>Complexity</td>
   <td>Higher (two keys in TPM)</td>
   <td>Lower (single key, just rewritten)</td>
  </tr>
</table>

**Resale / Re-provisioning:**

On resale, the Owner wipes the LDevID and/or DAK. The device falls
back to the next available key in preference order. If only an LDevID
was added, the device returns to IDevID -- as if it came directly from
the factory. If the DAK was rotated, the device has whatever DAK the
last Owner left it with (or no DAK, if it was deleted). A new Owner
onboards, and the cycle repeats.

**Mixed-State Considerations:**

The preference order is designed so that each entity (manufacturer,
Owner, next Owner) can act independently without needing to coordinate
identity strategy. However, mixed states can arise:

* A manufacturer provisions both IDevID and DAK. The FDO client uses DAK
  (priority 1). If the Owner later wipes the DAK, the device falls
  back to IDevID (priority 3) -- which may be unexpected if the Owner
  was not aware the IDevID existed.

* An Owner creates an LDevID (priority 2) but does not wipe the DAK
  (priority 1). The FDO client still uses the DAK. The LDevID is dormant
  until the DAK is removed.

* An Owner rotates the DAK and also creates an LDevID. The FDO client uses
  the rotated DAK (priority 1). The LDevID is dormant.

These states are all well-defined by the priority order, but
implementers SHOULD document which identity strategy they follow so
that subsequent operators know what to expect.

</div>


## Using IDevID or LDevID as the FDO Device Key ## {#DEVID_INTEROP}

When an IDevID or LDevID key (per [[TPMIdentKeys]]) is used as the
FDO Device key, the following requirements apply:

1. The IDevID or LDevID key SHALL be persisted in the TPM at a
   persistent handle. The persistent handle SHALL be recorded in
   `DCTPM.DeviceKeyHandle`. Once persisted, the key is usable directly
   by handle -- no parent key, hierarchy authorization, or key loading
   is required at runtime.
2. The provisioning entity (manufacturer, OEM, or platform integrator)
   SHALL create and populate the DCTPM NV index during Device
   Initialization (DI). The DCTPM SHALL include the correct
   `DeviceKeyType` value (1 for IDevID, 2 for LDevID). Without DCTPM,
   the FDO client cannot discover the device key.
3. The creation and management of IDevID and LDevID keys -- including
   hierarchy selection, key templates, certificate issuance, and CA
   ceremony -- is governed by the TCG DevID specification
   [[TPMIdentKeys]] and is outside the scope of this document.
4. IDevID and LDevID keys may use key algorithms beyond the FDO DAK
   templates defined in this specification, including RSA 2048 (TCG
   DevID Template H-1), ECC P-521 (H-4), and SM2 P-256 (H-5). The FDO
   protocol supports all key algorithms defined in the FDO specification;
   the DAK ECC templates in [[#KEYTEMPL_LABEL]] apply only to
   `DeviceKeyType=0`.

<div class="informative">

**DAK is the recommended default.** A purpose-built DAK (DeviceKeyType=0)
is under FDO's sole control: the FDO client and owner software can
create, rotate, and delete it without coordinating with any other
software on the system. For most deployments, a DAK is the simplest
and most reliable choice.

**IDevID keys** are provisioned by the TPM vendor or platform OEM
during manufacturing, using firmware-level TPM access.  An IDevID is
a permanent hardware identity -- it cannot be rotated or deleted by
the device Owner.  Because IDevID is non-rotatable, it is best suited
as a bootstrap identity for initial onboarding (see
[[#PRIVACY_IDEVID]]), after which the Owner provisions a DAK or LDevID
for ongoing use.

**LDevID keys are managed by external software, not by the FDO client.**
An LDevID is created and managed by a certificate authority (CA) workflow
-- typically an enterprise enrollment agent or platform identity service
-- that generates the key, issues a certificate, and registers the
certificate with relying parties.  The FDO client MAY *use* an LDevID
for signing if it is recorded in `DCTPM.DeviceKeyHandle`, but the FDO
client SHOULD NOT unilaterally create, rotate, or delete an LDevID.
Doing so would desynchronize the key from its certificate and from any
non-FDO software (e.g., 802.1AR network authentication, enterprise PKI
agents) that relies on the same LDevID.

Conversely, non-FDO software that manages LDevID keys (e.g., a DevID
enrollment agent) may rotate the LDevID at any time per its own policy.
If this happens while FDO credentials reference the old LDevID handle,
the Ownership Voucher's key binding becomes invalid and re-provisioning
is required.

**Unified identity deployments:** In systems where a single device
identity is desired across both FDO and DevID use cases, the FDO
client and the DevID management software MUST be designed as a
coordinated system -- sharing key lifecycle events, certificate
issuance, and rotation schedules.  This is an integration requirement
on the system designer, not something FDO can enforce unilaterally.
If such coordination is not feasible, use a DAK for FDO and keep the
LDevID independent.

The `userWithAuth` attribute on IDevID/LDevID keys follows the TCG DevID
convention (`userWithAuth=1, adminWithPolicy=1`), which is the same
default used by FDO DAK keys. The FDO client uses an empty-auth HMAC session
for signing, regardless of key type.

</div>


## FDO Client Boot Sequence ## {#BOOT_LABEL}

FDO client software (the FDO client) SHALL use the following sequence to
discover and use FDO credentials at boot:

1. Read the DCTPM NV index at handle `0x01D10001` using `TPM2_NV_Read`.
   If the NV index does not exist, the device has no FDO credentials
   and requires Device Initialization (DI).
2. Decode the CBOR structure and verify the magic value
   (`0x46444F31`). If the magic does not match, the DCTPM is
   not valid and the device requires DI.
3. Check `DCActive`. If false, FDO credentials are not initialized.
4. Extract `DeviceKeyHandle` and `HMACKeyHandle`.
5. Call `TPM2_ReadPublic` on `DeviceKeyHandle` to verify the key
   exists and to determine the key algorithm (ECC curve, RSA modulus
   size, hash algorithm). If `TPM2_ReadPublic` fails, the device
   key has been evicted and the device requires re-provisioning.
6. Call `TPM2_ReadPublic` on `HMACKeyHandle` to verify the HMAC key
   exists. If it fails, the device requires re-provisioning.
7. Use the keys with empty-auth HMAC session authorization:
   `TPM2_Sign(DeviceKeyHandle, ...)` for device attestation and
   `TPM2_HMAC(HMACKeyHandle, ...)` for credential verification.

<div class="informative">

The boot sequence is identical regardless of whether the device key is
a DAK (Type 0), IDevID (Type 1), or LDevID (Type 2). The
`DeviceKeyType` field is informational metadata useful for credential
management decisions (e.g., whether the key can be rotated), but does
not affect protocol behavior. The FDO client uses the key at the handle
recorded in DCTPM, regardless of type.

The FDO client does not need to know:
* Whether the key is a primary or ordinary (child) object
* Which hierarchy was used for creation
* Whether a parent key exists
* How to recreate the key

Once persisted via `TPM2_EvictControl`, TPM keys are stored unwrapped
in the TPM's internal NV and are usable directly by their persistent
handle. No parent key or hierarchy authorization is needed at runtime.

</div>


## FDO HMAC Secret ## {#HMAC_LABEL}

<div class="informative">

The HMAC secret, which is part of the FDO Secret Device Credentials,
is created in the TPM as a child key object under a storage parent
(typically the SRK) and is persisted at the handle
recorded in `DCTPM.HMACKeyHandle`.

<span style="text-decoration:underline;">Lifetime:</span>

The HMAC secret is changed when the FDO Public Device Credentials change.

**Note:** When the FDO Public Device Credentials are updated during
  the TO2 protocol, a new HMAC value is computed over the credentials
  for the new Ownership Voucher.

<span style="text-decoration:underline;">Storage:</span>

The HMAC secret is persisted in the TPM. The persistent handle
is recorded in `DCTPM.HMACKeyHandle` so that any compliant client can
locate and use the key without knowledge of how it was created.
Once persisted, the parent key (SRK) is not needed at runtime.


</div>

1. The HMAC secret SHALL be a keyed-hash key with the object attributes and template specified in [[#KEYTEMPL_LABEL]], including `fixedTPM=1`, `sensitiveDataOrigin=1`, `userWithAuth=1`, and `adminWithPolicy=1`.
2. The HMAC secret SHALL be persisted within the TPM via `TPM2_EvictControl`. The persistent handle SHALL be recorded in `DCTPM.HMACKeyHandle`.
    1. The HMAC secret SHALL be evicted and recreated during TO2, unless credential reuse is being performed (see [[#CREDREUSE_LABEL]]), in which case the existing HMAC secret is retained.

The same creation methods described for the Device key ([[#DEVKEY_LABEL]]) apply to the HMAC secret: the provisioning entity MAY create the key as a child key under a deterministic parent or as a Primary key with a unique string. The outcome — a persistent HMAC key at the specified handle, usable with empty authValue — is identical in both cases.

**Note:** Default Templates for the FDO HMAC secret are defined for HMAC-SHA256 and HMAC-SHA384.


## FDO Device certificate (OPTIONAL)  ## {#DEVCERT_LABEL}

Storing the FDO Device certificate in the TPM is OPTIONAL and is
rarely needed in practice. The certificate chain for the Device key
is already present in the Ownership Voucher, which is held by the
owner server — not the device. The FDO protocol does not require the
device to possess its own certificate.

If desired, the device certificate or certificate chain MAY be stored
in the TPM as an NV Index; see <a href="#TABNVINDEXHDL">Table 5</a>.

If the Device Key is the IDevID or the LDevID, the device certificate
is stored as described in the TCG DevID specification
[[TPMIdentKeys]]. 



# FDO Ownership Voucher (OPTIONAL) # {#OV_LABEL}

Storing a copy of the Ownership Voucher in the TPM is OPTIONAL and
is rarely used in practice. The Ownership Voucher is normally held
by the owner server and the device does not need a local copy for
FDO protocol operation. This facility exists only for narrow
supply-chain scenarios described below.

When the TPM manufacturer wishes to use the TPM chip itself to deliver
the Ownership Voucher to the Device Manufacturer, the TPM
manufacturer’s Ownership Voucher MAY be stored in the TPM as NV Index;
see <a href="#TABNVINDEXHDL">Table 5</a> 

This facility is provided for situations where the TPM manufacturer
desires to place FDO credentials in the TPM, to avoid the need for an
out of band transfer of the Ownership Voucher to the Device
manufacturer.  The Ownership Voucher MUST be pre-signed to a public
key owned by the Device Manufacturer. 

Since the Ownership Voucher is normally stored outside the Device, the
Device SHALL delete the Ownership Voucher after it has been
extracted. 

Upon storing the Ownership Voucher in the TPM, the DC.Active flag
SHALL be set to False.  The Device FDO software SHALL extract the
Ownership Voucher before setting the DC.Active flag to be True. 

<div class="informative">

This mechanism only applies to situations where the TPM manufacturer
can target specific TPM chips to a specific Device manufacturer (e.g.,
it might require a large batch of TPM’s). 

The Ownership Voucher is protected by a signature of the TPM
manufacturer, so this mechanism is equivalent to sending the Ownership
Voucher out of band, from a security point of view. 

Were the DC.Active flag set to True before the Ownership Voucher is
extracted, the Device would hang in FDO waiting for an Owner that will
never arrive. 


</div>



## TPM Operations on FDO Credentials ## {#TPMOPS_LABEL}

### Locating FDO Credentials in TPM ### {#Locating_LABEL}

To determine whether any FDO Credentials are stored in the TPM, the
The FDO client shall query the TPM for the presence of the handles defined in
this specification. 

<div class="informative">

The following commands can be used:



* TPM2_GetCapability (capability = TPM_CAP_HANDLES, property = TPM_HT_NV_INDEX) returns a list of NV Index handles present in the TPM.
* TPM2_GetCapability (capability = TPM_CAP_HANDLES, property = TPM_HT_PERSISTENT) returns a list of persistent object handles present in the TPM.


</div>

If the TPM has been provisioned with FDO Credentials, the TPM SHALL at least store  

* one DCTPM NV Index (containing DCActive, credentials, and key handles)
* one persistent Device Key object (at the handle recorded in `DCTPM.DeviceKeyHandle`)
* one persistent HMAC key object (at the handle recorded in `DCTPM.HMACKeyHandle`)

### Deleting FDO Credentials in TPM  ### {#Deleting_LABEL}

To invalidate the FDO credentials in the TPM, the following SHALL be deleted:  

* the DCTPM NV Index (using TPM2_NV_UndefineSpace)
* the persistent Device Key object (using TPM2_EvictControl)
* the persistent HMAC key object (using TPM2_EvictControl)

The following MAY also be deleted if present:



* LDevID used for the Device Key. 

IDevID used for Device Key is managed according to the rules for IDevID in [[TPMIdentKeys]]



# DEVICE INITIALIZATION AND STARTUP  # {#DEVICEInitStart_LABEL}

## Device Initialization for FDO ## {#DevInit_LABEL}

When the TPM is initialized for FDO, the FDO credentials are stored in the TPM, as specified in **Error! Reference source not found.**. 

Typically, FDO is run during the next boot after a successful
initialization for FDO. As such, Active SHOULD be set to True during
FDO credential initialization.  If specific manufacturing processes
require a boot without FDO, setting Active to True is deferred. 

<div class="informative">

TPM initialization for FDO can happen any time after the TPM manufacture, including:



* As part of manufacture of the TPM part
* As part of manufacture of the board-level computer using the TPM
* After completion of the board-level computer, but before operating system installation
* After operating system installation, during the supply chain
* After device has been in operation


</div>



## Device Startup with and without FDO ## {#DeviceWioutFDO_LABEL}

<div class="informative">

*   Use of SHOULD rather than MUST: A legacy OS that pre-dates this
    specification might not restrict access to the FDO credentials
    during runtime.

*   NV Indices can be created ahead, but not populated.
    This is assumed in the discussion of "empty" NV indices.

*   Related to items [5] and [6], below: A successful run of FDO causes
    the credentials to beupdated, so that FDO can run again.  In some
    situations, the product does not wish ever to run FDO again.  In
    this case, the FDO credentials can be deleted from the TPM by the
    FDO implementation after the successful run of the protocol.  In
    addition, the startup code that checks the FDO credentials is also
    able to delete these credentials, as a “belt and suspenders”
    security check.

*   As per FDO specification, FDO completes successfully in the Device
    when the message TO2.Done is transmitted. To ensure that this
    message is received, the FDO device waits (“dallies”) for a
    TO2.Done2 message to be received, so it can retransmit the
    TO2.Done message.


</div>

On device startup:



1. If the FDO software is not installed, the device SHOULD delete the stored FDO credentials, unless FDO software is intended to be installed later. FDO credential security relies on TPM authorization controls (hierarchy auth, key object attributes), not on execution-environment isolation.
2. If the content of FDO NV indices is “empty” (i.e. all Zero or TPMA_NV_WRITTEN is clear), then the FDO client or the shim layer SHALL not invalidate access to the FDO credentials and reset the authValue to the empty password. This allows a FDO credential provisioning to be executed in the context of the OS, whilst consumption of the FDO credentials remains limited to the FDO client.
3. If FDO software is installed, the FDO software SHALL query the TPM for FDO credentials, as described in ‎5.10.1.
4. If the FDO software cannot find credentials, FDO software SHALL terminate, and normal system startup ensues.
5. If Active == False, the FDO protocol SHALL NOT be executed, and normal system startup ensues. During this check, FDO credentials MAY be deleted, if it is known that FDO will not run again. Otherwise, modifications of the FDO credentials SHALL NOT occur.
6. If Active == True, FDO SHALL be run.

* If FDO completes successfully, the FDO TPM credentials SHALL be:
    * updated, and Active MAY be set to False
    * deleted  
* If FDO does not complete successfully, the FDO TPM credentials SHALL NOT be updated, and Active SHALL remain True.

# Other FDO Credentials Stored on Device # {#OTHERFDOCRED}

<div class="informative">

It is legal for a device to store FDO credentials in a device-specific manner, outside the TPM. In this case, it is device-dependent whether the TPM is queried for credentials.


</div>

A device which has both device-specific FDO credentials and TPM-based FDO credentials:



* MAY try each set of credentials in turn.
* MAY try the credentials in any order.
* SHOULD delete the unused set of credentials.

# Post-Onboarding Security Model # {#POSTONBOARD_LABEL}

<div class="informative">

The security requirements for FDO credentials differ significantly
between pre-onboarding and post-onboarding phases. This section
clarifies the threat model for each phase and defines the Owner's
post-onboarding access rights.

</div>

## Pre-Onboarding: Credential Integrity ## {#PREONBOARD_LABEL}

Before the first successful TO2, FDO credential integrity is critical.
The device has not yet been claimed by an Owner, and the credentials
must be intact for onboarding to succeed.

The following protections are sufficient for pre-onboarding integrity:

* **TPM key protections:** The Device Key is created with `fixedTPM=1`,
  `fixedParent=1`, `sensitiveDataOrigin=1`. The private key cannot be
  extracted from the TPM. This is the fundamental provenance guarantee
  and is independent of NV index protection.

* **HMAC binding:** The Ownership Voucher contains an HMAC computed
  over the device credentials using the HMAC secret inside the TPM. If
  an attacker modifies NV credential data but cannot control the HMAC
  key, the HMAC will not match the Ownership Voucher and TO2 will
  fail. Tamper is cryptographically detectable.

* **Platform hierarchy protection:** NV indices created with
  `TPMA_NV_PLATFORMCREATE=1` can only be deleted by Platform
  authorization. The manufacturer controls Platform hierarchy during
  the pre-onboarding window.

## At Onboarding Time: Proving Provenance ## {#ATONBOARD_LABEL}

During TO2, the critical security property is: the device can prove
that its Device Key genuinely resides in this TPM and corresponds to
the public key in the Ownership Voucher.

This is proven by the device signing protocol messages with the Device
Key. The TPM guarantees this signature can only be produced by the TPM
that holds the key. This property depends entirely on the TPM's key
protections -- not on NV index access controls.

## Post-Onboarding: Owner Access ## {#POSTONBOARD_ACCESS_LABEL}

After a successful TO2:

* The Owner has been mutually authenticated via the Ownership Voucher
* The Owner has full system control via FSIM
* The Owner can install arbitrary software, reflash the OS, replace
  the FDO client, rewrite credentials, or wipe the device entirely

Therefore, the Owner hierarchy SHOULD have read and write access to
all FDO credential NV indices after onboarding. The Owner SHOULD be
permitted to:

* Rewrite the DAK for credential reuse (see [[#CREDREUSE_LABEL]])
* Create an LDevID to replace the onboarding key
* Wipe all FDO credentials to decommission FDO
* Toggle the Active flag for resale

<div class="informative">

The DCActive flag is a field within the DCTPM CBOR structure.
The DCTPM NV index uses `OWNERWRITE=1`, `OWNERREAD=1`, empty authValue,
allowing the Owner to toggle the active flag, update credentials for
credential reuse, and manage key rotation — all through a single NV
index.

**Threat model clarification:**

The meaningful security boundary is the TPM's own key protections
(hardware-enforced, non-extractable keys). NV index access controls
provide a secondary layer that is useful pre-onboarding but SHOULD NOT
obstruct legitimate post-onboarding operations.

After onboarding, if malware has root access, the system is already
fully compromised. Protecting FDO credentials via NV index access
controls does not meaningfully improve the security posture. The
Device Key private material is always protected by TPM hardware
(`fixedTPM=1`), regardless of NV index attributes.

</div>

# Credential Reuse Pathways # {#CREDREUSE_LABEL}

After a successful TO2 onboarding, the Owner MAY enable subsequent
re-onboarding (credential reuse) by rotating the Device Key and
generating a new Ownership Voucher. The correct rotation strategy
depends on the current Device Key type:

**If the current key is a DAK** (`DeviceKeyType=0`): Replace the DAK
at the same persistent object handle and generate a new Ownership
Voucher. This is the straightforward case — the DAK is under FDO's
sole control. See [[#CREDREUSE_DAK]].

**If the current key is an IDevID** (`DeviceKeyType=1`): The IDevID
is a permanent hardware identity provisioned by the TPM or platform
manufacturer. It cannot be rotated or deleted by the device Owner.
To enable credential reuse, create a new DAK at a new persistent
object handle, update `DCTPM.DeviceKeyHandle` and set
`DCTPM.DeviceKeyType=0`, then generate a new Ownership Voucher
referencing the DAK. The IDevID remains in the TPM but is no longer
referenced by FDO. See [[#CREDREUSE_DAK]].

**If the current key is an LDevID** (`DeviceKeyType=2`): The LDevID
is managed by external identity management software (enterprise
enrollment agent, certificate authority) that also issues and
maintains the key's certificate. FDO client software SHOULD NOT
rotate an LDevID unilaterally — doing so would desynchronize the key
from its certificate and break any non-FDO system that relies on it.
If the system has been designed with a unified identity management
framework that coordinates both FDO credentials and DevID
certificates, the LDevID MAY be rotated through that framework.
Otherwise, create a new DAK at a new persistent object handle and
update DCTPM to reference the DAK instead. See [[#CREDREUSE_LDEVID]].

## Pathway A: Replace the DAK ## {#CREDREUSE_DAK}

The Owner (or Owner-installed software) creates a new Device Key in the
TPM, persists it at the same handle recorded in `DCTPM.DeviceKeyHandle`,
and generates a new Ownership Voucher referencing the new key's public
key. The old Ownership Voucher is cryptographically invalidated -- the
HMAC computed from the old credentials will not match.

A new child key is created via `TPM2_Create` under the same
deterministic parent primary, loaded via `TPM2_Load`, the old key is
evicted (`TPM2_EvictControl`), and the new key is persisted at the same
handle (`TPM2_EvictControl`). The DCTPM NV index is updated with
new credential data.

Requirements for Pathway A:

* The DCTPM NV index MUST be writable to update credential fields
  (GUID, RVInfo, PubKeyHash).
* The entity performing the replacement MUST have access to the TPM's HMAC
  operation to generate the new Ownership Voucher.
* The new Ownership Voucher MUST be generated on the device, because
  the HMAC secret cannot be extracted from the TPM.
* The entity MUST have Owner authorization to call `TPM2_EvictControl`
  for persisting the new key.

<div class="informative">

Provisioning entities SHOULD design their key storage to permit
post-onboarding replacement. This is the natural consequence of
mandatory persistence and handle-based discovery: the Owner simply
replaces the key at the handle.

</div>

## Pathway B: Create an LDevID ## {#CREDREUSE_LDEVID}

This pathway transitions the FDO Device Key from a DAK to an LDevID,
unifying FDO device identity with the TCG DevID identity framework.

The creation of an LDevID key and its associated certificate is
governed by the TCG DevID specification [[TPMIdentKeys]] and typically
involves a certificate authority (CA) workflow -- an enterprise
enrollment agent, platform identity service, or similar system
software that generates the key, issues a certificate, and registers
the certificate with relying parties (e.g., 802.1AR network
infrastructure, enterprise PKI systems).

Once an LDevID has been created and persisted by this external
process, FDO credentials MAY be updated to reference it: set
`DCTPM.DeviceKeyType=2` and `DCTPM.DeviceKeyHandle` to the LDevID's
persistent handle, then generate a new Ownership Voucher referencing
the LDevID's public key.

FDO client software SHOULD NOT unilaterally create, rotate, or
delete an LDevID. The LDevID's certificate and the relying parties
that trust it are managed outside of FDO. If FDO software were to
rotate the TPM key without coordinating with the certificate
authority and enrollment infrastructure, the key would become
desynchronized from its certificate -- invalidating not only FDO
credentials but also any non-FDO identity system (network
authentication, asset management, remote attestation) that depends
on the same LDevID.

Requirements for Pathway B:

* The DCTPM NV index MUST be writable to update DeviceKeyType and
  DeviceKeyHandle.
* The entity performing the update MUST have access to the TPM's HMAC
  operation to generate the new Ownership Voucher.
* LDevID key creation and certificate issuance MUST be performed by
  the appropriate identity management system, not by FDO client
  software acting alone.

<div class="informative">

**Integration guidance:** If a deployment requires a single unified
device identity across both FDO and DevID use cases, the FDO
credential management software and the DevID enrollment/CA software
MUST be designed as a coordinated system -- sharing key lifecycle
events, certificate issuance, and rotation schedules. This is an
integration requirement on the system designer. FDO provides the
mechanism (handle-based key reference in DCTPM) but cannot enforce
cross-system coordination.

If such coordination is not feasible, use Pathway A (replace the DAK)
for FDO credential reuse and keep the LDevID independent. The DAK is
under FDO's sole control and can be rotated without affecting any
other identity system.

</div>

## Operational Note: New Ownership Voucher Generation ## {#CREDREUSE_NEWOV}

Both pathways require generating a new Ownership Voucher after
changing the device key reference. This operation requires:

1. The new device key's public key or certificate
2. The ability to compute an HMAC inside the TPM (the HMAC secret
   cannot leave the TPM)
3. Writing updated credential data (GUID, RVInfo, PubKeyHash) to the
   DCTPM NV index

Because the HMAC secret is non-exportable, the new Ownership Voucher
MUST be generated by an entity with TPM access -- typically the
Owner's management agent or FDO client running on the device.

<div class="informative">

This is a natural consequence of the TPM security model: any
credential reuse flow requires on-device TPM operations. Remote
Owner servers cannot generate new Ownership Vouchers without the
HMAC secret.

</div>

# Privacy and Identity Lifecycle # {#PRIVACY_LABEL}

<div class="informative">

This section is entirely informative and provides guidance on privacy
considerations across the FDO credential lifecycle.

## IDevID as Bootstrap Identity ## {#PRIVACY_IDEVID}

IDevID is the permanent hardware identity -- analogous to a birth
certificate. It proves manufacturing provenance but SHOULD NOT be
the long-term FDO credential referenced in Ownership Vouchers that
circulate through the supply chain.

The key preference order ([[#KEYPREF_LABEL]]) supports a model where
IDevID serves as a **bootstrap identity**:

1. IDevID is used for the initial onboarding when no DAK or LDevID
   exists
2. After onboarding, the Owner provisions a DAK or LDevID
3. A new Ownership Voucher is created referencing the DAK/LDevID
4. IDevID returns to dormant state -- still in the TPM, still
   provable if needed, but not referenced in the active OV
5. On resale, the Owner wipes the DAK/LDevID; the device falls back
   to IDevID for the next onboarding
6. The cycle repeats with the new Owner

IDevID is only visible to each new Owner during the brief initial
onboarding handshake, not in any persisted Ownership Voucher that
circulates through supply chain intermediaries.

## LDevID for Owner-Scoped Privacy ## {#PRIVACY_LDEVID}

LDevID provides cross-owner unlinkability:

* Owner 1 onboards with IDevID, issues LDevID-1, creates OV
  referencing LDevID-1
* On resale, Owner 1 wipes LDevID-1
* Owner 2 onboards with IDevID (brief exposure), issues LDevID-2,
  creates OV referencing LDevID-2
* Owner 1 cannot correlate via LDevID-1 (wiped), Owner 2 does not
  see LDevID-1

Each owner operates with their own LDevID. The IDevID is exposed only
momentarily during ownership transitions.

## Factory Reset Scenarios ## {#PRIVACY_RESET}

The key preference order and rewritable credentials enable several
reset scenarios:

**Soft Reset (wipe LDevID/DAK, keep IDevID):**

The device falls back to IDevID for the next onboarding. This is
equivalent to returning the device to its manufacturing identity. The
previous Owner's LDevID/DAK is erased, removing their identity from
the device. The device can be re-onboarded as if it came directly from
the factory.

Privacy note: IDevID is a permanent identifier. If previous owners
retained the IDevID public key (from earlier Ownership Vouchers or
onboarding logs), the device is correlatable across owners via IDevID.
This is acceptable when device tracking is desired (e.g., enterprise
asset management) and mitigated by the LDevID model when privacy is
required.

**Hard Reset (wipe everything, re-initialize):**

All FDO credentials are deleted, including DAK and potentially LDevID.
The device requires fresh Device Initialization (DI). If the IDevID is
retained, it can serve as the bootstrap key for re-initialization. If
the IDevID is also wiped (via `TPM2_ChangeEPS` or equivalent), the
device has no provable identity and must be treated as a blank device.

This is the strongest anonymity option: no previous owner or
manufacturer can correlate the device to its history. However, hardware
provenance is also lost. This tradeoff is appropriate for specific use
cases (e.g., device decommissioning, regulatory requirements for data
destruction).

**Privacy-Preserving Resale (LDevID rotation):**

The selling Owner issues a transitional LDevID (or allows the buying
Owner to do so via credential reuse per [[#CREDREUSE_LABEL]]), then
wipes all previous LDevIDs. The new OV references only the new LDevID.
The selling Owner's identity is erased from the device, and the buying
Owner has a fresh owner-scoped identity.

This is the recommended approach when privacy across ownership
boundaries is required.

</div>

# FDO NV and KEY Templates # {#TEMPLATES}

This section defines default Templates for the FDO Device key
([[#DEVKEY_LABEL]]) and FDO HMAC secret ([[#HMAC_LABEL]]). Fields that
are common to the default Templates of both keys (object attributes
and authorization) are defined in [[#Storage_LABEL]]. 



## Attributes for FDO NV Indices ## {#Attributes_LABEL}

<div class="informative">

FDO keys are created as ordinary child keys under a deterministic
parent primary (SRK). Each key is generated from the TPM's RNG
(`sensitiveDataOrigin=1`), producing a unique and unpredictable key.
Keys are persisted via `TPM2_EvictControl` at permanent handles.

To preserve FDO credentials across a `TPM2_Clear`, the parent primary
and persistent key objects should be created under the Platform
hierarchy (which survives `TPM2_Clear`). Keys created under the Owner
hierarchy are removed by `TPM2_Clear` and must be re-provisioned.

</div>

The following NV Index attribute settings SHOULD be used for the FDO Public Device Credentials.
The attribute profiles below are RECOMMENDED defaults. The provisioning
entity MAY adjust these attributes to match their deployment model,
provided the NV index handles and data formats remain as specified.
In particular, after a successful TO2 onboarding, the Owner MAY
redefine NV indices with OWNERWRITE=1 and OWNERREAD=1 to enable
credential reuse and key rotation (see [[#POSTONBOARD_LABEL]]).


